  "\\label{ex:homotopy}\n  \\ref{def:homotopy}\nLet\n$$\n\\gamma_0(t) = (t,0), \\quad \\gamma_1(t) = (t,t), \\quad t \\in [0,1].\n$$\n\nBoth paths go from $(0,0)$ to $(1,1)$.\n\nDefine a homotopy $H : [0,1] \\times [0,1] \\to \\mathbb{R}^2$ by\n$$\nH(t,s) = (t, s t).\n$$\n\n\nProof that this is infact a homotopy: \n\n\n\\textbf{Initial path:}\n$$\nH(t,0) = (t,0) = \\gamma_0(t).\n$$\n\n\\textbf{Final path:}\n$$\nH(t,1) = (t,t) = \\gamma_1(t).\n$$\n\n\\textbf{Endpoints:}\n$$\nH(0,s) = (0,0), \\quad H(1,s) = (1,s).\n$$\n\nThus, $H$ defines a homotopy between $\\gamma_0$ and $\\gamma_1$.",
  :type :example,
  :title "An Example of a Homotopy",
  :concepts [],
  :label "ex:homotopy",
  :id "d65691cf",
  :source-file "algebraic-topology.tex",
  :area "Algebraic Topology",
  :depends-on ["c4860b45"],
  :created-at "2026-03-27"}
