 {:tags [],
  :proof-latex nil,
  :refs ["def:representation" "def:character" "def:direct-sum-rep"],
  :latex
  "Let $\\rho_1 : G \\to \\mathrm{GL}(V_1)$ and $\\rho_2 : G \\to \\mathrm{V_2}$ be two linear representations of $G$ (Definition \\ref{def:representation}), and let $\\chi_1$ and $\\chi_2$ be their characters (Definition \\ref{def:character}).\n  Then:\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n    \\item The character of the direct sum representation (Definition \\ref{def:direct-sum-rep}) is equal to $\\chi_1 + \\chi_2$.\n    \\item The character of the tensor product representation $V_1 \\otimes V_2$ is equal to $\\chi_1 \\cdot \\chi_2$.\n  \\end{enumerate}",
  :type :proposition,
  :title "",
  :concepts [],
  :label nil,
  :id "8aabc776",
  :source-file "lie-groups.tex",
  :area "Lie Groups and Lie Algebras",
  :depends-on ["4e94b0c3" "e83c1383" "36d19f67"],
  :created-at "2026-03-27"}
 {:tags [],
  :proof-latex nil,
  :refs ["def:character" "def:representation" "def:inner-product"],
  :latex
  "\\label{def:inner-product}\n  The inner product of two characters (Definition \\ref{def:character}) of representations of a finite group $G$ (Definition \\ref{def:representation} is\n  \\[\n    \\langle \\chi_1, \\chi_2 \\rangle = \\frac{1}{|G|}\\sum_{g \\in G} \\chi_1 (g) \\overline{\\chi_2(g)}\n  \\]\n\n  \\begin{remark}\n    The inner product of two characters (Definition \\ref{def:inner-product}) for a finite group is a sort of \"averaging\" over character values\n    for a finite group. Keep this in mind when we define a similar notion for compact Lie groups using the Haar measure. Intuitively, averaging\n    over continuous symmetries require making the sum finer and finer, which turns into an integral!\n  \\end{remark}",
  :type :definition,
  :title "Inner Product",
  :concepts [],
  :label "def:inner-product",
  :id "ecf76e5d",
  :source-file "lie-groups.tex",
  :area "Lie Groups and Lie Algebras",
  :depends-on ["e83c1383" "4e94b0c3"],
  :created-at "2026-03-27"}
