  "\\label{def:category} \nA \\emph{category} $\\mathcal{C}$ consists of the following data:\n\\begin{enumerate} \n  \\item A collection of objects, denoted $\\operatorname{Ob}(\\mathcal{C})$. \n  \\item For every pair of objects $X,Y \\in \\operatorname{Ob}(\\mathcal{C})$, a set $$ \\operatorname{Hom}_{\\mathcal{C}}(X,Y) $$ whose elements are called \\emph{morphisms} (or arrows) from $X$ to $Y$. \n  \\item For every triple of objects $X,Y,Z$, a composition map $$ \\operatorname{Hom}_{\\mathcal{C}}(Y,Z) \\times \\operatorname{Hom}_{\\mathcal{C}}(X,Y) \\to \\operatorname{Hom}_{\\mathcal{C}}(X,Z), $$ written $$ (g,f) \\mapsto g \\circ f . $$ \n  \\item For every object $X$, an identity morphism $$ \\operatorname{id}_X \\in \\operatorname{Hom}_{\\mathcal{C}}(X,X). $$ \n  \\end{enumerate} \nThese data satisfy the following axioms: \n\\begin{enumerate} \n\\item \\textbf{Associativity:} For morphisms $$ X \\xrightarrow{f} Y \\xrightarrow{g} Z \\xrightarrow{h} W $$ we have $$ h \\circ (g \\circ f) = (h \\circ g) \\circ f . $$ \n\\item \\textbf{Identity:} For every morphism $f : X \\to Y$, $$ f \\circ \\operatorname{id}_X = f \\qquad\\text{and}\\qquad \\operatorname{id}_Y \\circ f = f . $$ \\end{enumerate}",
  :type :definition,
  :title "Category",
  :concepts [],
  :label "def:category",
  :id "f2c6bdf5",
  :source-file "category.tex",
  :area "Category Theory",
  :depends-on [],
  :created-at "2026-03-27"}
 {:tags [],
